<a href="javascript:card_browser(64)">Fool of a Took!</a><br>
<br>
     </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> This deck is insane!  If you are thinking about giving a bad review, please go and try the deck for yourself first and you&#39;ll probably reconsider.<br>
<br>
Fellowship:  The concept here is to stay healthy.  Never move twice and try to stay behind your opponent.  You can make use of your starting site or if your opponent starts pony you can use that too.  Try to get out as many guys as possible and use your hobbit stealth events while you can to avoid damage.  Don&#39;t worry about twilight, trust me.  It may seem like your taking alot of damage, but remember you&#39;ve got nine guys so you can drop a few and still get along.  Try to get your card drawing engines up fast (e.g. delving, elrond etc.)  and draw as many cards as you can each turn.  At the end of your fellowship phase, place most if not all of your orcs on the bottom of the deck, you&#39;ll see why later. Just remeber, you&#39;ll never win through fellowship and it only takes 1 skirmish phase to overwhelm your opponent&#39;s frodo 80 to 4.<br>
<br>
Shadow:  Here&#39;s the real deck.  The idea is to stack the bottom of your deck with as many orcs as possible.  When I play it I turn the cards under my deck sideways so I know where the orc swarm starts but if your opponent objects it just takes a simple count of the cards you place under your deck.  If your opponent plays any hobbit other than Frodo its game over and you win cause when you go through your deck fool of a took will put roughly 20 orcs into your hand.  Even if they don&#39;t have another hobbit that concentration of orcs along with all the card drawing mechanisms is still insane overtkill.  There&#39;s a savage and a snows to stop PATHS and anything else to help the weak little ring bearer.  Don&#39;t worry about getting them for the onslaught, remember, you go through your whole deck.  The optimal site to lay down the victory is 7 since it cancels archery.  With on archery and no skirmish events/abilities your opponent will just look at his hand and clean up his deck.  The 4 Cave Trolls are to slow your opponent down if he decides to try and sprint the 9 sites so you can&#39;t go through your deck.  I usually put 1 of the trolls with the orcs at the bottom to ensure my victory under any circumstance.  Now your probably wondering &quot;How does he get all the twilight for 20 orcs, a cave troll, a savage and a snows?&quot;  Goblin Armories.  Once you get 4 out (you will every game, you go through your whole deck)  scimitars cost -4 twilight and draw a card.  Also, half your orcs paly for nothing. Runners are -1 and Scouts are 0 if you spot an elf, not to hard.  Thats about all I have to say so go and try out the deck for yourself and you&#39;ll understand what i&#39;m talking about.<br>
<br>
Thanks for Reading. </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN="2"><font class="bfont"> <a href="/lotr/decks/decks.php">Back to Decks Directory</a> | <A HREF="/lotr/decks/decks.php?reviews=21605"> Read Reviews </A> | <a href="deckprint.php?deck=21605" TARGET="BLANK_"> Printer Friendly</a></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><a name="review"></a><font class="h2font">In order to review decks you must be a registered member. <A href="/lotr/main/join.php">Sign up for free!</A></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
